goterms.name: positive regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. Endothelial cells are thin flattened cells which line the inside surfaces of body cavities, blood vessels, and lymph vessels, making up the endothelium.

goterms.name: negative regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiostatin binding
goterms.description: Binding to angiostatin, a proteolytic product of plasminogen or plasmin containing at least one intact kringle domain, and which is an inhibitor of angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenin-PRI complex
goterms.description: A stable heterodimer of angiogenin and placental ribonuclease inhibitor; interaction between angiogenin and PRI prevents angiogenin binding to its receptor to stimulate angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of vascular endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway by insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: Any process in which internalization of an insulin receptor stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signal transduction. Internalization of insulin in association with its receptor clears insulin from the circulation and is necessary for subsequent insulin dissociation from the receptor and insulin degradation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin secretion
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway by insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: Any process in which internalization of an insulin receptor activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the insulin receptor signaling pathway. Endocytosis of activated receptors can concentrate receptors within endosomes and allow the insulin receptor to phosphorylate substrates that are spatially distinct from those accessible at the plasma membrane.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

goterms.name: angiogenesis
goterms.description: Blood vessel formation when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels.

goterms.name: regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: regulation of sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: regulation of angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenesis involved in wound healing
goterms.description: Blood vessel formation when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels and contribute to the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

goterms.name: sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The extension of new blood vessels from existing vessels into avascular tissues, this process includes the specialization of endothelial cells into leading tip and stalk cells, proliferation and migration of the endothelial cells and cell adhesion resulting in angiogenic sprout fusion or lumen formation.

goterms.name: intussusceptive angiogenesis
goterms.description: The formation of new blood vessels as a result of the insertion and extension of lumenal tissue pillars.

goterms.name: cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of blood vessel endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population contributing to sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell migration involved in intussusceptive angiogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during intussusceptive angiogenesis.

goterms.name: regulation of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: regulation of cell adhesion involved in intussusceptive angiogenesis
goterms.description: The process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of attachment of a blood vessel endothelial cell to another cell or to the extracellular matrix involved in intussusceptive angiogenesis.

goterms.name: cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The attachment of a cell, either to another cell or to an underlying substrate such as the extracellular matrix, via cell adhesion molecules that contributes to the formation of a blood vessel network.

goterms.name: regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: alpha6-beta1 integrin-CYR61 complex
goterms.description: A protein complex that consists of an alpha6-beta1 integrin complex bound to CYR61, a cysteine-rich protein involved in angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenic sprout fusion
goterms.description: The connection of an angiogenic sprout to another vessel or sprout during the formation of vascular networks by sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell migration
goterms.description: The orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during angiogenesis.

goterms.name: endothelium development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an endothelium over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Endothelium refers to the layer of cells lining blood vessels, lymphatics, the heart, and serous cavities, and is derived from bone marrow or mesoderm. Corneal endothelium is a special case, derived from neural crest cells.

goterms.name: positive regulation of endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of vascular endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: regulation of endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: regulation of vascular endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial cell proliferation.

goterms.name: vascular endothelial cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of blood vessel endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

goterms.name: cellular ketone body metabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone, as carried out by individual cells. Although 3-hydroxybutyrate is not a ketone, it is classed as a ketone body because it exists in an equilibrium with acetoacetate. Ketone bodies may accumulate in excessive amounts in the body in starvation, diabetes mellitus or in other defects of carbohydrate metabolism.

goterms.name: cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an insulin stimulus. Insulin is a polypeptide hormone produced by the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas in mammals, and by the homologous organs of other organisms.

goterms.name: glucose import in response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: The directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell as a result of an insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: glucose metabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucose, the aldohexose gluco-hexose. D-glucose is dextrorotatory and is sometimes known as dextrose; it is an important source of energy for living organisms and is found free as well as combined in homo- and hetero-oligosaccharides and polysaccharides.

goterms.name: insulin binding
goterms.description: Binding to insulin, a polypeptide hormone produced by the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas in mammals, and by the homologous organs of other organisms.

goterms.name: insulin catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of insulin.

goterms.name: insulin metabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving insulin.

goterms.name: insulin receptor complex
goterms.description: A disulfide-bonded, heterotetrameric receptor complex. The alpha chains are entirely extracellular, while each beta chain has one transmembrane domain. The ligand binds to the alpha subunit extracellular domain and the kinase is associated with the beta subunit intracellular domain.

goterms.name: insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the movement of an insulin receptor from the plasma membrane to the inside of the cell.

goterms.name: insulin receptor recycling
goterms.description: The process that results in the return of an insulin receptor to an active state at the plasma membrane. An active state is when the receptor is ready to receive an insulin signal. Internalized insulin receptors can be recycled to the plasma membrane or sorted to lysosomes for protein degradation.

goterms.name: insulin receptor signaling pathway via phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase
goterms.description: An insulin receptor signaling pathway in which the signal is transmitted via the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase cascade.

goterms.name: insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the insulin receptor binding to insulin.

goterms.name: insulin receptor substrate binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin receptor substrate (IRS) protein, an adaptor protein that bind to the transphosphorylated insulin and insulin-like growth factor receptors, are themselves phosphorylated and in turn recruit SH2 domain-containing signaling molecules to form a productive signaling complex.

goterms.name: insulin receptor activity
goterms.description: Combining with insulin receptor ligand and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin-like growth factor, any member of a group of polypeptides that are structurally homologous to insulin and share many of its biological activities, but are immunologically distinct from it.

goterms.name: insulin-responsive compartment
goterms.description: A small membrane-bounded vesicle that releases its contents by exocytosis in response to insulin stimulation; the contents are enriched in GLUT4, IRAP and VAMP2.

goterms.name: regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell proliferation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle hypertrophy
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle hypertrophy.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle tissue growth
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle growth.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle fiber development
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber development. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle tissue development
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle tissue development.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle tissue regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle regeneration.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell differentiation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell proliferation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle hypertrophy
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle hypertrophy.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle tissue growth
goterms.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of skeletal muscle growth.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle fiber development
goterms.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of skeletal muscle fiber development. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle tissue development
goterms.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of skeletal muscle tissue development.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle tissue regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increase the rate of skeletal muscle regeneration.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell differentiation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle adaptation
goterms.description: Any process in which skeletal muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors. These adaptive events occur in both muscle fibers and associated structures (motoneurons and capillaries), and they involve alterations in regulatory mechanisms, contractile properties and metabolic capacities.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell proliferation.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle hypertrophy
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle hypertrophy.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle tissue growth
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle growth.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle adaptation
goterms.description: Any process in which skeletal muscles change their phenotypic profiles in response to altered functional demands and a variety of signals.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle atrophy
goterms.description: A process, occurring in skeletal muscle, that is characterized by a decrease in protein content, fiber diameter, force production and fatigue resistance in response to different conditions such as starvation, aging and disuse.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of skeletal muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle fiber differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a skeletal muscle fiber cell. Skeletal muscle fiber differentiation starts with myoblast fusion and the appearance of specific cell markers (this is the cell development step). Then individual skeletal muscle fibers fuse to form bigger myotubes and start to contract.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle hypertrophy
goterms.description: The enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of an organ due to an increase in size (not length) of individual muscle fibers without cell division. In the case of skeletal muscle cells this happens due to the additional synthesis of sarcomeric proteins and assembly of myofibrils.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of satellite cells, resulting in the expansion of the cell population. Satellite cells are quiescent cells that are located between the basal lamina and the plasmalemma of the muscle fiber, which are the main contributors to postnatal muscle growth. In adult muscle, satellite cells become activated to divide and differentiate in response to muscle damage.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle tissue development
goterms.description: The developmental sequence of events leading to the formation of adult skeletal muscle tissue. The main events are: the fusion of myoblasts to form myotubes that increase in size by further fusion to them of myoblasts, the formation of myofibrils within their cytoplasm and the establishment of functional neuromuscular junctions with motor neurons. At this stage they can be regarded as mature muscle fibers.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle tissue growth
goterms.description: The increase in size or mass of a skeletal muscle. This may be due to a change in the fiber number or size.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle tissue regeneration
goterms.description: The regrowth of skeletal muscle tissue to repair injured or damaged muscle fibers in the postnatal stage.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle fiber development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeletal muscle fiber over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle cell differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a skeletal muscle cell, a somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell maintenance involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Any process by which the number of skeletal muscle satellite cells in a skeletal muscle is maintained during muscle regeneration. There are at least three mechanisms by which this is achieved. Skeletal muscle satellite stem cell asymmetric division ensures satellite stem cell numbers are kept constant. Symmetric division of these cells amplifies the number of skeletal muscle satellite stem cells. Some adult skeletal muscle myoblasts (descendants of activated satellite cells) can develop back into quiescent satellite cells, replenishing the overall pool of satellite cells.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a satellite cell.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell commitment
goterms.description: The process in which the developmental fate of a cell becomes restricted such that it will develop into a satellite cell.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell activation
goterms.description: The change of a skeletal muscle satellite cell from a mitotically quiescent to a mitotically active state following exposure to some activating factor such as a cellular or soluble ligand. In adult muscle, satellite cells become activated to divide and differentiate in response to muscle damage.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell migration
goterms.description: The orderly movement of a skeletal muscle satellite cell from one site to another. Migration of these cells is a key step in the process of growth and repair of skeletal muscle cells.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell fate specification
goterms.description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a skeletal muscle satellite cell in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway. Upon specification, the cell fate can be reversed.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite cell fate determination
goterms.description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a skeletal muscle satellite cell regardless of its environment; upon determination, the cell fate cannot be reversed.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite stem cell asymmetric division
goterms.description: The asymmetric division of a skeletal muscle satellite stem cell to produce two daughter cells, one of which is destined to differentiate and the other to be a quiescent cell that restocks the satellite cell pool.

goterms.name: initiation of skeletal muscle satellite cell activation by growth factor signaling, involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Signalling between growth factors and their receptors that results in the activation of satellite cell, where this process is involved in skeletal muscle regeneration. Satellite cells are quiescent cells that are located between the basal lamina and the plasmalemma of the muscle fiber, which are the main contributors to postnatal muscle growth. In adult muscle, satellite cells become activated to divide and differentiate in response to muscle damage.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite stem cell asymmetric division involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Skeletal muscle satellite cell asymmetric division that occurs during a process in which damaged muscle tissue is being rebuilt.

goterms.name: symmetric division of skeletal muscle satellite stem cell
goterms.description: The symmetric division of a skeletal muscle satellite stem cell, resulting in two skeletal muscle satellite stem cells. This process is involved in amplification of the pool of these cells.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle satellite stem cell maintenance involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Any process by which the number of skeletal muscle satellite stem cells in a skeletal muscle is maintained during skeletal muscle regeneration. There are at least two mechanisms by which this is achieved. Skeletal muscle satellite stem cell asymmetric division ensures satellite stem cell numbers are kept constant. Symmetric division of these cells amplifies the number of skeletal muscle satellite stem cells.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell activation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell activation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration.

goterms.name: positive regulation of satellite cell activation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activation of satellite cell involved in skeletal muscle regeneration. The activation of satellite cell is the process that initiates satellite cell division by causing it to move from quiescence to the G1 stage of the cell cycle. The cell swells and there are a number of other small changes. The cells then start to divide. Following cell division the cells will differentiate.

goterms.name: regulation of satellite cell activation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell activation. The satellite cell activation is the process that initiates satellite cell division by causing it to move from quiescence to the G1 stage of the cell cycle. The cell swells and there are a number of other small changes. The cells then start to divide. Following cell division the cells will differentiate.

goterms.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell proliferation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell differentiation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of growth factor dependent skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell proliferation; dependent on specific growth factor activity such as fibroblast growth factors and transforming growth factor beta.

goterms.name: positive regulation of growth factor dependent skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell proliferation; dependent on specific growth factor activity such as fibroblast growth factors and transforming growth factor beta.

goterms.name: growth factor dependent regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of satellite cell proliferation; dependent on specific growth factor activity such as fibroblast growth factors and transforming growth factor beta.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle satellite cell proliferation.

goterms.name: satellite cell activation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process that initiates skeletal muscle satellite cell division by causing it to move from quiescence to the G1 stage of the cell cycle. The cell swells and there are a number of other small changes. The cells then start to divide. Following cell division the cells will differentiate. In adult muscle, satellite cells become activated to divide and differentiate in response to muscle damage.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle thin filament assembly
goterms.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins to form the actin-based thin filaments of myofibrils in skeletal muscle.

goterms.name: skeletal muscle myosin thick filament assembly
goterms.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins to form the myosin-based thick filaments of myofibrils in skeletal muscle.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle fiber development
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber development. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle tissue development
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle tissue development.

goterms.name: myoblast proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of myoblasts, resulting in the expansion of a myoblast cell population. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast division
goterms.description: The process resulting in the physical partitioning and separation of a myoblast into daughter cells. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the myoblast over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fate specification
goterms.description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a myoblast in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway. Upon specification, the cell fate can be reversed. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fate commitment
goterms.description: The process in which the developmental fate of a cell becomes restricted such that it will develop into a myoblast. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast maturation
goterms.description: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for a myoblast to attain its fully functional state. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast migration
goterms.description: The orderly movement of a myoblast from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism. A myoblast is a cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fate determination
goterms.description: The cell fate determination process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a myoblast regardless of its environment; upon determination, the cell fate cannot be reversed. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fusion
goterms.description: A process in which non-proliferating myoblasts fuse to existing fibers or to myotubes to form new fibers. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: regulation of myoblast differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of myoblast differentiation. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: positive regulation of myoblast differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of myoblast differentiation. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: negative regulation of myoblast differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of myoblast differentiation. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast migration involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which a myoblast migrates along an entire fiber to the site of injury. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast differentiation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized satellite cell acquires specialized features of a myoblast. This occurs as part of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast proliferation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of myoblasts, resulting in the expansion of the cell population. This occurs as part of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fusion involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: A process in which non-proliferating myoblasts, after migrating to the site of injury, fuse into existing damaged fibers or fuse to myotubes to form new fibers, as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fate specification involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which a satellite cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a myoblast in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway. Upon specification, the cell fate can be reversed. This occurs as part of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast maturation involved in muscle regeneration
goterms.description: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for a myoblast cell to attain its fully functional state involved in muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myotube differentiation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotube differentiation starts with myoblast fusion and the appearance of specific cell markers (this is the cell development step). Then individual myotubes can fuse to form bigger myotubes and start to contract. This process occurs as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

goterms.name: myotube cell development involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process aimed at the progression of a myotube cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. This occurs as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle tissue regeneration
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle cell differentiation.

goterms.name: regulation of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation.

goterms.name: myoblast fate determination involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which a satellite cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a myoblast regardless of its environment; upon determination, the cell fate cannot be reversed. This occurs as part of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: myoblast fate commitment involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
goterms.description: The process in which the developmental fate of a satellite cell becomes restricted such that it will develop into a myoblast. This occurs as part of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

goterms.name: skeletal myofibril assembly
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeletal myofibril over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A skeletal myofibril is a myofibril specific to skeletal muscle cells.

goterms.name: muscle hypertrophy
goterms.description: The muscle system process that results in enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of a muscle organ due to an increase in the size of its muscle cells. Physiological hypertrophy is a normal process during development (it stops in cardiac muscle after adolescence) and can also be brought on in response to demand. In athletes cardiac and skeletal muscles undergo hypertrophy stimulated by increasing muscle activity on exercise. Smooth muscle cells in the uterus undergo hypertrophy during pregnancy.

goterms.name: muscle alpha-actinin binding
goterms.description: Binding to muscle isoforms of actinin. Muscle alpha-actinin isoforms are found in skeletal and cardiac muscle and are localized to the Z-disc.

goterms.name: striated muscle cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of striated muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. Striated muscles contain fibers that are divided by transverse bands into striations, and cardiac and skeletal muscle are types of striated muscle.

goterms.name: striated muscle tissue development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a striated muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Striated muscle contain fibers that are divided by transverse bands into striations, and cardiac and skeletal muscle are types of striated muscle. Skeletal muscle myoblasts fuse to form myotubes and eventually multinucleated muscle fibers. The fusion of cardiac cells is very rare and can only form binucleate cells.

goterms.name: striated muscle cell development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a striated muscle cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Striated muscle cells contain fibers that are divided by transverse bands into striations, and cardiac and skeletal muscle are types of striated muscle.

goterms.name: regulation of myofibril number
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the number of myofibrils. A myofibril is the contractile element of skeletal and cardiac muscle. It is a long, highly organized bundle of actin, myosin, and other proteins that contracts by a sliding filament mechanism.

goterms.name: regulation of myofibril size
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the size of myofibrils. A myofibril is the contractile element of skeletal and cardiac muscle. It is a long, highly organized bundle of actin, myosin, and other proteins that contracts by a sliding filament mechanism.
